Virat Kohli is an Indian international cricketer who is widely regarded as one of the greatest batsmen in the history of cricket. He is currently the captain of the India national team and has been a key player for the team since his debut in 2008.

Kohli was born on November 5, 1988, in Delhi, India. He began playing cricket at a young age and quickly rose through the ranks to become one of the top players in India. In 2011, he made his Test debut against Sri Lanka and has since played over 150 Tests for India.

Kohli is known for his aggressive and dynamic batting style, which has earned him numerous accolades and records. He has scored over 27,000 runs in international cricket, including 25 centuries (100s) and 69 half-centuries (50s). He is also one of the fastest players to reach 10,000 runs in international cricket.

In addition to his impressive batting record, Kohli has also been an influential leader on the field. He was appointed as the captain of the India national team in 2016 and led the team to numerous victories, including a World Cup win in 2019. He is known for his strong leadership qualities and ability to motivate his teammates.

Kohli has also been involved in various philanthropic activities and has worked with several charitable organizations over the years. He has been recognized for his contributions to cricket and has won numerous awards, including the Arjuna Award (2013) and the Padma Shri (2020).

Some of Kohli's notable achievements include:

* Highest run-scorer in Test cricket among India
* Fastest player to reach 10,000 runs in international cricket
* Winner of the ICC World Cup with India in 2019
* Awarded the Arjuna Award (2013) and the Padma Shri (2020)

Overall, Virat Kohli is a highly accomplished cricketer who has made significant contributions to the sport. He continues to be one of the most successful batsmen in international cricket and remains an influential leader on the field.